post_text:
Life-saving suicide prevention training is available to school communities in San Joaquin County.

Youth suicide rates are rising, and nearly 1 in 5 students say they’ve seriously considered suicide in the past year. How can we keep them safe? With the right knowledge and skills, school communities can be a lifeline of hope for students.

The LivingWorks Start training is available to middle and high school teachers in San Joaquin County through the San Joaquin County Office of Education (SJCOE). The next wave of training will include students.

For access to the training, contact Nora Hana at nhana@sjcoe.net and (209) 221-9488.

Download the flyer for more information: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1rnwu2Lp7xfRK8gPIHam4tCwhcBD2rtmJ/view?usp=sharing

The summit will feature musicians, speakers, and performers raising awareness for youth mental health and suicide prevention.

#LWYouthSummit #Lavendaire #AileenXu #SuicidePrevention #YouthMentalHealth
shared_text:
California Department of Education
August 19 at 4:40 PM ·

On September 15, 2020, LivingWorks Education will be holding the first-ever virtual LivingWorks Youth Summit. The online event will livestream from 1-2 p.m. PST, and will be available via YouTube following the livestream.

Aileen Xu, also known as Lavendaire, a Youtube personality and content creator, will be guest speaking. Aileen is an inspirational content creator whose mission is to share her knowledge about personal growth and mental health while inspiring her audience to cultivate their "dream life." Aileen's online persona, Lavendaire, is a resource for personal growth and lifestyle design, as developed on her YouTube channel and podcast.

Read more about her and the event at lwyouthsummit.com

#LWYouthSummit #Lavendaire #AileenXu #SuicidePrevention #YouthMentalHealth

Do you have a Bachelor’s Degree in communications, English, writing, or a related field? If so, the SJCOE might have the perfect job opportunity for you as a Grant Development Coordinator.

The Grant Development Coordinator serves as a resource for the development and preparation of grant applications and proposals for public and private funding sources; prepares and disseminates materials concerning available grants, awards, and related programs; provides grant writing training; and maintains resources to be used by county office of education staff in the development of grants.

To learn more about this position and to apply, visit https://www.edjoin.org/Home/DistrictJobPosting/1325593. Application deadline is Sept. 18.

post_text: Congrats again to Hank Chau on being named the North Central Valley STEM Center (NCVSC) STEM Teacher of the Year! 🎉 Read more about the "STEM-ulating" Elkhorn educator being honored this week in this latest article from Lodinews.
shared_text:
Lodinews
August 26 at 6:28 PM ·

STEM-ulating: Elkhorn educator honored

When Elkhorn Elementary School teacher Hank Chau was visited by his principal and representatives from the San Joaquin County Office of Education in his classroom Tuesday morning, he thought they were there only to film him teaching science, technology, engineering and mathematics curriculum.
Little did he know, though, they were visiting to present him with the Albert Brocchini Memorial STEM Teacher of the Year award.
Brett States, the STEM Director with the SJCOE, presented Chau with a plaque as he conducted a Zoom session with his 10:30 a.m. class. Nominated by his eighth grade students Caden Cao and Haroon Abdulgader, Chau said it was all the students he teaches that made the award special.

For the full story, visit www.lodinews.com

Congressman Jerry McNerney will be hosting a virtual town hall on distance learning and the digital divide on Tuesday, Aug. 25 from 4:30 – 6 PM.

With the COVID-19 pandemic forcing many schools to shift from in-person classrooms to distance learning, the town hall will focus on what is being done at the federal and local levels to meet these challenges, and how distance learning and the digital divide have impacted students, parents, and teachers.

The town hall panel will feature Federal Communications Commissioner Jessica Rosenworcel, Contra Costa County Superintendent of Schools Lynn Mackey, San Joaquin County Superintendent of Schools James Mousalimas, and San Joaquin Delta College President Dr. Omid Pourzanjani.

To participate online: https://zoom.us/j/99883818132?pwd=T0RZeFFzS0x6VnhUUHNXcXU0bmVxZz09#success

To participate by phone: (669) 900-6833

Webinar ID: 998 8381 8132

Webinar Passcode: 967360

AT&T is expanding the Access from AT&T program, which provides home internet access to qualifying California households with at least one resident who receives Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) or Supplemental Security Income (SSI) benefits for $10 a month. 💻

According to AT&T, they do not charge a fee to apply or process applications and no deposit is required to establish internet service under the program. Additionally, in response to COVID-19, Access from AT&T is temporarily expanding eligibility based on income and to households participating in National School Lunch Program/Head Start and waiving all home internet data overage fees. Residents who would like more information about Access from AT&T can visit att.com/access or call 1-855-220-5211.

For other internet connectivity options, please visit https://sjcoe.org/healthsafety/resourcesforclass.aspx.

post_text:
Please join us in congratulating Mavis Thomas, the August 2020 Special Education Programs Educator of the Month! 🎉

The 2020-21 school year marks the fifth year that Mavis has taught preschool-autism classes at McFall School in Manteca. 🏫 When asked what Mavis loves most about teaching, she stated, “I love seeing each student learn something new, no matter how big or small the skill, whether it’s sitting during circle time for a whole song or simply giving a high five upon request.”

Mavis chose a career in education because she genuinely enjoys helping and nurturing others. 🧡 Plus, working with children keeps her on her toes! Per Mavis, the best part about working at McFall is the wonderful students and awesome staff.

A fun fact that students and colleagues might not know about Mavis is that she has a swimming pool but doesn’t know how to swim unless you count doggy paddling! 😉

Venture Academy Family of Schools students, teachers, and staff have been gearing up for the new school year this week! Along the SJCOE campus, students and families have been visiting Venture’s drive-thru and outdoor pick-up stations to receive laptops, laptop chargers, whiteboards, and other materials needed to begin distance learning. Students at some of the academies also had the opportunity to take their Student ID photo as they picked up their class schedules.

Although the start of the new school year is quite different, the excitement and optimism that a new school year brings were still present. "This is an exciting and unique new school year," an eleventh-grade student at Excel Academy said, while a teacher at Kinect Academy said, “It's nice seeing the students again!” 💙 #BacktoSchoolSJC

Schools and districts continued to load up on PPE stored and distributed by the SJCOE, with Tracy Unified, Manteca Unified, Ripon Unified, Tracy Learning Center, and more picking up equipment this week.

The California Department of Education and theCalifornia Governor's Office of Emergency Services is distributing PPE and other supplies to schools through county offices of education throughout California. So far in San Joaquin County, that amounts to 36,600 bottles of hand sanitizer, 18,240 N95 respirator masks, 208,000 adult-size surgical masks, 164,000 child-size surgical masks, 24,480 plastic face shields, and 1,200 non-contact infrared thermometers for school districts and charter schools.

post_text:
The SJCOE's Special Education Programs administration team on Tuesday assembled bundles of personal protective equipment and cleaning supplies for 100 special education classrooms and 400 employees.

Each individual employee will receive a cloth mask, a face shield, hand sanitizer, and gloves. Classroom kits contain disinfectant wipes, germicidal bleach, face masks, spray bottles, hand sanitizer, and organizational trays. All items in the bundles were purchased by Special Education with the guidance of special education classroom nursing staff and SJCOE Operations & Support Services.

Classroom instruction is still on hold due to COVID-19, but the Special Education staff will be ready when it resumes.

shared_text:
RECORDNET.COM
'Passionate about her students': Sierra High's Rachel Hernandez named SJ's 2020 Teacher of the Year

Recordnet.com
July 23 at 1:51 AM ·

When parents want to learn sign language so they can communicate better with their children, Rachel Hernandez offers free classes in her personal time. If another teacher needs help, she’s there. If she needs help, another teacher is there for her. The program is like a family. Her passion and dedication earned Hernandez, a teacher at Sierra High in Manteca, the 2020 San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year title from the San Joaquin County Office of Education. “It means everything,” Hernandez said. “I am definitely doing it for the kids. That’s why I go to work every day.”

Lodi Unified School District visited the SJCOE campus on Thursday to load up on PPE (personal protective equipment). Several large trucks picked up multiple pallets of supplies that will be delivered to individual school sites, available to students and staff when they return to campus.

The California Department of Education and the California Governor's Office of Emergency Services is distributing PPE and other supplies to schools through county offices of education throughout California. So far in San Joaquin County, that amounts to 36,600 bottles of hand sanitizer, 18,240 N95 respirator masks, 208,000 adult-size masks, 164,000 child-size masks, 24,480 plastic face shields, and 1,200 non-contact infrared thermometers for school districts and charter schools.

post_text:
The recognition of the San Joaquin County Teacher of Year celebrates all teachers as well as our county's legacy of excellence in education.

The first was Hal Michaels, Lincoln Elementary School (Manteca Unfired School District), who was selected as San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year in 1973. Nominees, finalists, and teachers of the year followed until the selection of Jeff Simpfenderfer, Liberty High School (Lodi Unified School District), the 2019 Teacher of the Year.

In between, three San Joaquin County educators went on to be state teachers of the year:
Paulette Bogetti (1992, Lincoln Elementary School, Manteca Unified School District), Jeff Wright (2000, Lincoln High School, Lincoln Unified School District), and Art Coleman (2003, Hamilton Middle School, Stockton Unified School District).

Each district, through their superintendent’s office, may submit up to three candidates for consideration for the County Teacher of the Year.

The 2020 San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year will be announced by video on the SJCOE Facebook page on Friday at 5 p.m.
text:
The recognition of the San Joaquin County Teacher of Year celebrates all teachers as well as our county's legacy of excellence in education.

The first was Hal Michaels, Lincoln Elementary School (Manteca Unfired School District), who was selected as San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year in 1973. Nominees, finalists, and teachers of the year followed until the selection of Jeff Simpfenderfer, Liberty High School (Lodi Unified School District), the 2019 Teacher of the Year.

In between, three San Joaquin County educators went on to be state teachers of the year:
Paulette Bogetti (1992, Lincoln Elementary School, Manteca Unified School District), Jeff Wright (2000, Lincoln High School, Lincoln Unified School District), and Art Coleman (2003, Hamilton Middle School, Stockton Unified School District).

Each district, through their superintendent’s office, may submit up to three candidates for consideration for the County Teacher of the Year.

The 2020 San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year will be announced by video on the SJCOE Facebook page on Friday at 5 p.m.

post_text: Learn something new on Thursday, July 9, at the next bi-weekly CodeStack (virtual) Meetup. Besides teaching the next generation of coders, CodeStack is helping build the growing tech community right here in Stockton and San Joaquin County with events like this. #WeAreSJCOE
shared_text:
CodeStack Academy
July 8 at 4:33 PM ·

Learn to integrate API into your web project!
Have you ever wondered how other sites interact with big name sites like Google, Facebook, or Pinterest? Maybe you want information or functionality from those other sites have but don't have time to build it yourself.

Well, in some cases, API's help you do this. A lot of functionality can be pulled into your website with a few lines of code creating a simple API call.

Mark Hypolite will be demonstrating "JavaScript Fetch API", a library native to JavaScript that allow you to communicate with any available API. During this presentation he will give a brief overview about what an API is and how they can be used and he will give you a quick peek into API code.

#CodeStack #SJCOE #Coding #CodeForGirls

post_text: The California Department of Education (CDE) will lead a series of virtual ethnic studies webinars on Facebook Live in the coming weeks. These webinars will help students, educators, and families familiarize themselves with the core areas of ethnic studies, including how different groups have struggled and worked together, as well as key concepts such as equality, justice, race, ethnicity, and indigeneity.

• Tuesday, July 14th, 3 p.m. to 4:30 p.m.: Chicano Latino Studies with Assemblymember Jose Medina and Dolores Huerta

• Tuesday, July 21st, 3 p.m. to 4:30 p.m.: Asian American Studies with Karen Korematsu

• Tuesday, July 28th, 2 p.m. to 3:30 p.m.: Native American Studies with Assemblymember James C. Ramos

SJCOE Artists In Schools Ms. Patti is back to present us with Albert Bierstadt’s painting, Looking Up The Yosemite Valley. Today, Ms. Patti will tell us about Bierstadt’s self-portrait in the painting and will guide us as we draw ourselves as the artist ✏️ and find different ways to fill in the landscape background.

Bierstadt’s monumental landscapes were influential in creating a sense of pride in the natural wonders of the United States leading to support of the national parks initiative. 🏞️💚

You can learn more about the painting at https://hagginmuseum.org/collections/bierstadt-albert/looking-up-the-yosemite-valley/.

💻Find more videos and resources in the #LOCkER at www.sjcoe.org/LOCkER!

The SJCOE and North Stockton Rotary collected more than 1900 children's book donations through their Drive-Up/Drop-Off Children's Book Drive today.

Book-donors drove through drop-off points at both the one.Charter Elementary and one.Field of Dreams North drop-off locations in Stockton throughout the day. Volunteers greeted them with smiles as cars dropped off books at Pre-K through fourth-grade reading levels.

"Books bring us together. We want to bring the community together," said Lorie Liddicoat, former president of the North Stockton Rotary and incoming membership district chair for Rotary District 5220.

All donations will be distributed throughout the San Joaquin County community: to local classrooms, libraries, students, book buses, preschools, and after-school programs.

Thank you to everyone who donated today to the book drive. Your donations are promoting a love of reading for San Joaquin County students and increasing literacy in our community.

#WeAreSJCOE one.Program - San Joaquin County Office of Education

Free online Introduction to Web Development class at 6 p.m. on Thursday. Perfect for high school students, open to all.

The class is part of a CodeStack Meetup, held biweekly by CodeStack Academy to help build the growing tech community right here in Stockton and San Joaquin County.

It's free and it's live, so you can ask questions as you learn. Learn more at https://www.meetup.com/codestack.

#wearesjcoe #stockton #sanjoaquincounty
shared_text:
CodeStack Academy
June 20 at 7:14 PM ·

In this meetup we will be looking at one of the common frameworks used today, Bootstrap. Matthew Hicks will explain why so many people use it, when it came about, and how to use it. We will dive into the grid system and the many components available for us in Bootstrap framework. We will also take a look at our favorite part of Bootstrap, responsiveness. Come and join us on June 25 for an exciting lecture and find out why Bootstrap is one of the best frameworks available!

Also, Web Designer, Louie Ambriz will be available at the end of our meetup to answer any design related question in our "Ask A Designer" segment. Please bring your current projects, so we can take a look at anything you might want assistance.

Join us for this free virtual class at https://zcu.io/3BGy

#SJCOE #CodeSTack #Bootstrap #HTML #CSS #Coding #Programming #Stockton #209 #VisitStockton

post_text: Free online suicide prevention training program available to middle and high school staff and students throughout the state.
shared_text:
California Department of Education
June 17 at 10:34 PM ·

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond announced today that the CDE, in collaboration with the San Diego County Office of Education, is launching a free online suicide prevention training program available to middle and high school staff and students throughout the state.

The online training program is called LivingWorks Start, an evidence-based program that is aligned with CDE’s Model Youth Suicide Prevention Policy to address the needs of high-risk populations. According to a recent report by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, suicide is the second leading cause of death for youth ages ten to twenty-four.

Read more: https://www.cde.ca.gov/nr/ne/yr20/yr20rel44.asp

post_text:
Congratulations to Laura Sudderth, one of the five finalists for San Joaquin County Teacher of the year we have been celebrating this week. This third-grade instructor has taught at Lincoln Elementary School (Manteca Unified School District) for 31 years.

"Mrs. Sudderth is 'that teacher.' The teacher we all aspire to be, the teacher we want our own kids to have, the teacher that makes our younger generation want to be teachers. Parents request her and visitors to her class rave about the exceptional learning environment that she provides," writes Lincoln Elementary Principal Randi Fowzer in her nomination. "Not only is (Sudderth's classroom) warm and inviting to all, but you can immediately see and feel the connections that she is making with her students."

Congratulations to Laura Sudderth!

And congratulations to all the five finalists to be San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year. The winner will be announced in the fall. The winning teacher will be the San Joaquin County nominee for the California Teacher of the Year.

Three cheers for Laura La Rue, one of the five finalists for San Joaquin County Teacher of the year we are celebrating this week. This English teacher at Bear Creek High School (Lodi Unified School District) has been an educator for 23 years.

"What truly elevates Ms. La Rue as an exemplary teacher is her ability to meet the needs of all students," writes Bear Creek High Principal Hillary Harrell in her nomination. "Ms. La Rue monitors her students very closely throughout her instruction, and she adjusts it as necessary to meet their needs. Most teachers with her level of experience would not ask others for help, but Ms. La Rue continually asks for suggestions, especially for students who struggle."

Congratulations Laura La Rue!

We will continue to highlight San Joaquin County's Teacher of the Year nominees this week. The winner will be announced in the fall. The winning teacher will be the San Joaquin County nominee for the California Teacher of the Year.

post_text: Do you have new or gently used children’s books that you are looking to donate? Please consider dropping them off at the Children’s Book Drive on June 25! Your donations will be distributed to local classrooms, libraries, and students.
shared_text:
North Stockton Rotary
June 10 at 10:57 PM ·

Mark your calendars for Thursday, June 25th

North Stockton Rotary has partnered up with San Joaquin County Office of Education in an effort to put books in the hands of children in our community. Pre-K - 4th Grade Books collected from this book drive will go to libraries, classrooms, and programs where students can share the joy of reading.

Two drop off locations to choose from on Thursday, June 25th, 10:00AM - 3:00PM:
22 S. Van Buren Street, Stockton or 800 Douglas Road, Stockton

North Stockton Rotary collects hundreds of books for schools in our community each year as well as puts a dictionary in the hands of over 1,300 3rd grade students. Due to COVID19, we were unable to raise funds at our annual event that contributes to these amazing projects. We would like to thank Port of Stockton, Verve , and CI &SC (Karen Rea) for sponsoring this year's Dictionary Project and for allowing us to continue with our mission to promote literacy in our community.

post_text:
This week we are announcing five outstanding teachers who have been selected as finalists for the San Joaquin County Teacher of the Year award. First up is Linda Davis, eighth-grade teacher at Shasta Elementary School in the Manteca Unified School District.

"She is the stuff that Marvel Comics superheroes are made of, in the form of an exceedingly humble, dedicated and successful instructor who has taken students on an academic journey, many of whom thought was not possible until they met her," Shasta Principal Audrey Parker said when nominating Davis. She also added that Davis, "has the uncanny ability to teach confidence and self-respect to students who naively presumed they were only going to learn about algebra in their year spent with her."

Congratulations Linda Davis!

We will continue to highlight San Joaquin County's Teacher of the Year nominees this week. The winner will be announced in the fall. The winning teacher will be the San Joaquin County nominee for the California Teacher of the Year.

For more information, please visit: https://caparentyouthhelpline.org/

post_text:
Before the beginning of the drive-through promotion ceremony for the eighth-graders at VISA Academy on Tuesday, teacher Brandi Medeiros hosted a quick Zoom meeting online for the class, who were mostly in cars parked in the parking lot outside the classroom.

Medeiros waved and smiled at her students as they joined the chat. She gave a short speech, choking up at times before queuing up a slideshow with photos from the past two years.

"Work hard, be kind, and you will achieve great things," she told her class before heading outside to hand out certificates, each one with a handwritten note attached.

Across the San Joaquin County Office of Education (SJCOE) campus an hour earlier, another promotion ceremony at Kinect Academy. Both are academies at the Venture Academy Family of Schools charter.

The day's vehicle ceremonies marked the end of eighth-grade promotion and high-school commencement ceremonies for Venture Academy students that began last week.

#WeAreSJCOE #Classof2020

Under the guidance of coach Bob Oprandy and his wife Pat Tirone of the Delta Sculling Center, the Discovery ChalleNGe Academy sculling team 🚣🏽 set a new record in the ⏱️ 10 minute co-ed relay for their age division! The team rowed 2,699 meters in just 10 minutes, placing third🥉in the United States and Canada. Way to go, cadets!

To learn more about Erg Ed, visit https://www.pocockfoundation.org/erg-ed.

NOMINATE A STEM EDUCATOR OR STUDENT BY JUNE 20!

Do you know an outstanding STEM (science, technology, engineering, and math) student or teacher? If so, you can nominate them for one of the following awards currently available through the North Central Valley STEM Center:

1. Albert Brocchini Memorial STEM Teacher of the Year ($1,000)

2. Mel Cardenas Memorial CTE Student of the Year ($500)

3. North Central Valley STEM Student of the Year ($500)

These awards are open to educators and students from CCESA Region 6 counties: Amador, Calaveras, San Joaquin, Stanislaus, and Tuolumne.

Please download the applications and review the specific requirements for each award at https://www.sjcoescience.org/north-central-valley-stem-cent…. All applications must be submitted by June 20, 2020.

___________________________________________________

Amador County Office of Education, Calaveras County Office of Education, Stanislaus County Office of Education, and Tuolumne County Superintendent Of Schools Office.

California Healthy Kids Resource Center
May 21 at 3:40 PM ·

On June 9 from 5-6:30 PST: The Stanford Tobacco & Vaping Toolkit Team are thrilled to be hosting their second webinar for parents, educators, healthcare providers, and anyone interested in learning about vaping and young people.

If you weren’t able to attend the first webinar, or just want to hear more, please join in!

Please share with your parent groups!
Topics the Stanford team will cover include…
• Introduction to e-cigs/vaping/cannabis
• Health effects, including in light of COVID-19
• Which vapes are popular
• Why youth are using vapes
• Ways to support youth to not use and/or quit
• Q & A with audience (there will be plenty of time for questions)

#vapingdangers, #youthvaping, #vapingandlungdisease, #effectsofvaping, #vapingprevention #vapingeducation #vapingmyths #vapingandcovid19 #covid19dangers #vapinghealtheffects #vapingyouth #dangerofvaping #vapingeffects

post_text:
The Ventureland Academy school year ended with a splash. Staff from the Venture Academy Family of Schools academy for K-5 students volunteered to be targets in a drive-thru water-balloon toss on Wednesday.

"Especially this year, it feels really good to give them a smile," said Mark Condit, who along with Daniel Soza and Joshua Brigham, volunteered to sit in chairs while the students threw water balloons at them from a safe distance. The fun activity was scheduled to coincide when students normally come to the school to pick up meals.

There were no shortage of smiles from the children, their families, and Venture staff. Anthony and his sister Genesis beamed after they had their chance to hurl the balloons. Genesis said she was smiling for two reasons. The first was because she hit her target. The second was because she got to see people from the school she missed. "I'm happy," the first-grader said.

🍎 It's Classified School Employee Week! The SJCOE would like to take this time to recognize our classified employees for their tireless efforts and the expertise they provide to students, families, schools, and districts. Their diverse talents and true dedication are essential to the future of our youth.

Classified employees, thank you for everything you do for our students and community including providing transportation, meals, instruction, office support, and maintenance. YOU are the backbone of our public education system and we appreciate all YOU do to support education in San Joaquin County the whole year through! ✏️ #WeAreSJCOE

post_text:
California Day of the Teacher

Teachers and counselors - YOU are an integral part of our educational system, supporting each student’s individual needs so they can be successful in school and life.

For many of our students, YOU have been the guiding star in their lives and have made a profound impact toward their future goals.

Your positive impact on our students is more significant and important than ever during this global health crisis. YOU have continued to provide instruction and support to your students while families are sheltered at home. Your efforts are truly inspirational.

YOU deserve our sincere appreciation, and today YOU are celebrated and honored for providing the gift of knowledge through teaching.

Thank you for all you do to support the students and families we serve. #WeAreSJCOE

post_text:
Organizations helping families who are in economic distress or have been the victims of crimes received a little extra help today.

SJCOE Associate Superintendent Troy Brown passed on donations of personal hygiene kits and other items from Amazon.com to sites across San Joaquin County.

They reached the San Joaquin County District Attorney's Family Justice Center and Women's Center - Youth & Family Services, which provide valuable assistance to families when they need it the most.

The goods were also dropped off at community centers in Stockton and Tracy operated by CPFSJ (Community Partnership for Families of San Joaquin). Even with on-site services restricted due to stay-at-home orders and social districting, the nonprofit organization is still keeping in touch with families and providing goods at curbside pickups.

San Joaquin County's most-vulnerable children and families benefit when organizations and individuals pitch in to help. #WeAreSJCOE #StrongerTogetherSJC

May 9, 2020, would have marked this year’s California State Elementary Spelling Bee. Although we are unable to gather for this event due to the current circumstances, the SJCOE would like to recognize the 34 students from 17 counties that worked hard to do well at their county bee and qualify for the State Bee. We hope that all of our spellers continue to practice their love for reading and spelling.

Please join us in celebrating these bright, young scholars in the comments below.

post_text:
Let's take five with this simple breathing exercise!

1. Stretch your hand out like a star. 🌟

2. Get your pointer finger ready to trace your fingers up and down. ✋

3. Slide up ⬆️ each finger slowly. Then, slide down ⬇️ the other side.

4. Breath in through your nose and out through your mouth. 😤

5. Put it all together and breathe in as you slide up and breath out as you slide down. Keep going until you have finished tracing your hand.

We hope you will join us for these fun themed spirit day activities and try out the suggested positive coping strategies as we bring awareness to California’s first Student Mental Health Week!

🎼 Music Monday: Wear your favorite band shirt or dress up like your favorite musician.

🏝️ Cruise Day Tuesday: Dress up like you are going on a relaxing beach vacation.

🏋🏽 Workout Wednesday: Show off your workout gear! Bonus points for it being 80’s themed.

🎩 Thinking Cap Thursday: Wear your favorite hat, a funny hat, a party hat, or creative headwear.

🎽 Flannel Friday: Put on your comfy pajamas or sweat suit outfit.

For more resources, visit https://covid19k12counseling.org/. #CA4studentwellness

post_text: Congratulations to Hoover Elementary School's Mr. McCarty and his sixth grade students on taking first place in the 2020 California Water Service H2O Challenge for their project Water Collectors: Recycle, Reduce, Reuse! #Educate #Innovate #Inspire
shared_text:
CALWATER.COM
2020 Cal Water H2O Challenge Winners

California Water Service
April 27 at 11:45 PM ·

We’re happy to announce the winners of the 2020 Cal Water H2O Challenge! 🏆 With the current health emergency, this year’s announcements to the students were made virtually, but we could still feel their excitement through the computer! Here’s a sneak peek of the grand-prize surprise announcement, and catch the full reveal here: bit.ly/35beiVD

Grand prize: Shawn McCarty’s 6th-grade class at Hoover Elementary (Stockton)
2nd place: Tammy Janos’ 5th-grade class at Parkview Elementary (Chico)
3rd place: Kristen Thomas’ 4th-/5th-graders at Little Chico Creek Elementary (Chico)
4th place: Emily Akimoto’s 4th-grade class at Sierra View Elementary (Chico)
5th place: Mike Buckley’s 5th-graders at Murdock Elementary (Willows)

We’re so proud of these young water warriors and all of the classes that participated this year. The projects were out of this 🌎. Learn more about their projects: bit.ly/2SceVZI
